data.content:
**What happened:** C# 14 introduces new built-in span conversions. The compiler now resolves `array.Contains(num)` to `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. The `MemoryExtensions` overload cannot be represented in a LINQ expression tree, so it throws at runtime.

**Fix â€” use any of these approaches:**

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three force the compiler to bind to `Enumerable.Contains`, which is expression-tree-safe. The same issue affects `.Reverse()` on arrays (now resolves to the in-place `Span` version) â€” the same fix pattern applies.
